since `csurf` is [deprecated](https://expressjs.com/2025/05/16/express-cleanup-legacy-packages.html), the current recommended replacement for SPAs is [`csrf-csrf`](https://github.com/Psifi-Solutions/csrf-csrf) (double submit cookie pattern, which is exactly what axios implements).

**express setup:**

```ts
import cookieParser from 'cookie-parser';
import { doubleCsrf } from 'csrf-csrf';

app.use(cookieParser());

const { generateToken, doubleCsrfProtection } = doubleCsrf({
  getSecret: () => process.env.CSRF_SECRET,
  cookieName: 'XSRF-TOKEN',           // matches axios default
  cookieOptions: {
    sameSite: 'strict',
    secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',
    httpOnly: false,                    // MUST be false so axios can read it
  },
  getCsrfTokenFromRequest: (req) => req.headers['x-xsrf-token'],
});

// seed endpoint - call this on app init
app.get('/api/csrf-token', (req, res) => {
  generateToken(req, res);
  res.json({ ok: true });
});

app.use(doubleCsrfProtection); // validates all state-changing requests
```

**axios side** (what you already have is fine):

```ts
const api = axios.create({
  baseURL: getAPIUrl(),
  withCredentials: true,
  withXSRFToken: true,
});

// seed the cookie on app init
await api.get('/api/csrf-token');
// now all subsequent POST/PUT/DELETE requests auto-include X-XSRF-TOKEN header
```

the critical alignment: `csrf-csrf` defaults to reading `x-csrf-token` (not `x-xsrf-token`), so the `getCsrfTokenFromRequest` override is needed. and `httpOnly: false` is required or JS/axios can't read the cookie.

