In modern versions of Axios (v0.22+), the recommended way to cancel requests is by using the AbortController API, which replaces the older CancelToken approach.

Example with React:

```
import axios from "axios"
import { useEffect, useState } from "react"

function Users() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([])

  useEffect(() => {
    const controller = new AbortController()

    axios.get("/api/users", {
      signal: controller.signal
    })
    .then(res => {
      setUsers(res.data)
    })
    .catch(err => {
      if (err.name !== "CanceledError") {
        console.error(err)
      }
    })

    return () => {
      controller.abort()
    }
  }, [])

  return (
    <div>
      {users.map(u => (
        <p key={u.id}>{u.name}</p>
      ))}
    </div>
  )
}
```

AbortController allows Axios to cancel the request when controller.abort() is called.

This pattern is recommended for React components to prevent updating state after a component has unmounted and to avoid unnecessary network activity.
